{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.16,0.07,0.43,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116112"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98108"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1824"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43097"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116112"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of intermittent coughing and wheezing. These symptoms only occur about 15 minutes after he starts vigorous exercise and last for about 20 minutes. At the same time, he experiences some chest tightness and shortness of breath. His symptoms have begun to bother him more as he is now playing professional football. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 84/min, blood pressure 110/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate medication to use before exercise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formoterol","Montelukast","Tiotropium","Budesonide-formoterol","Budesonide"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EExercise-induced bronchoconstriction (EIB) is a common condition affecting up to 90% of people with asthma and 10-20% of athletes without underlying asthma. It is particularly prevalent in endurance athletes and those participating in winter sports or swimming. The condition is characterised by transient airway narrowing that occurs during or after vigorous exercise, typically beginning 10-15 minutes after initiating exercise and resolving spontaneously within 20-30 minutes. The pathophysiology involves airway cooling and drying during exercise, leading to bronchial hyperresponsiveness and bronchoconstriction. Diagnosis is confirmed through exercise challenge testing, which demonstrates a 10% or greater fall in FEV1 after exercise, though in clinical practice the diagnosis is often made based on characteristic history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudesonide-formoterol\u003C/strong\u003E (ICS-LABA combination) is now the recommended first-line treatment for exercise-induced bronchoconstriction. Current guidelines have shifted from the traditional approach of using short-acting beta-2 agonists (SABAs) as needed to recommending ICS-LABA combinations for both maintenance and reliever therapy. This combination provides immediate bronchodilation through formoterol (which has a rapid onset of action similar to SABAs) while the budesonide component provides anti-inflammatory effects that help prevent future episodes. When used 15-20 minutes before exercise, it provides effective prophylaxis against EIB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormoterol\u003C/strong\u003E alone is a long-acting beta-2 agonist with rapid onset of action. While it can provide effective bronchodilation, using a LABA without an ICS is not recommended as monotherapy in asthma due to safety concerns and lack of anti-inflammatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMontelukast\u003C/strong\u003E, a leukotriene receptor antagonist, can be effective for EIB and may be considered as add-on therapy if symptoms are not adequately controlled with ICS-LABA therapy. However, it is not first-line treatment and requires daily dosing for several days before achieving full effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETiotropium\u003C/strong\u003E, a long-acting muscarinic antagonist, is reserved for patients with moderate to severe asthma not adequately controlled with ICS-LABA combinations. It is not indicated as first-line therapy for EIB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudesonide\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while providing anti-inflammatory effects, lacks the rapid bronchodilation needed for pre-exercise prophylaxis. The onset of action for inhaled corticosteroids alone is too slow to prevent EIB when taken immediately before exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe evolution in treatment recommendations reflects growing evidence that regular use of SABAs can lead to tachyphylaxis and paradoxically worsen exercise tolerance. The ICS-LABA combination approach provides both immediate symptom relief and long-term disease control, making it ideal for athletes who require reliable protection during training and competition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExercise should not be avoided in patients with exercise-induced asthma. Non-pharmacologic interventions may include breathing warm, humidified air, greater emphasis on pre-exercise warm-up, and decreasing the magnitude of minute ventilation. These can be used in conjunction with pharmacological management for optimal control of EIB.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Budesonide-formoterol (ICS-LABA combination) is now recommended as first-line therapy for both maintenance and reliever treatment in exercise-induced bronchoconstriction.","Exercise-induced bronchoconstriction affects up to 90% of people with asthma and 10-20% of athletes without underlying asthma.","Diagnosis is confirmed by demonstrating a 10% or greater fall in FEV1 after exercise challenge testing."],"references":["National Asthma Council Australia. (2025). Exercise and asthma. Australian Asthma Handbook, The National Guidelines for Health Professionals. (Version 3.0). Accessed 24 September 2025. https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/clinical-topics/exercise-and-asthma","Koya T, Ueno H, Hasegawa T, Arakawa M, Kikuchi T. Management of Exercise-Induced Bronchoconstriction in Athletes. The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice. 2020 Jul;8(7):2183\u201392. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32620432/","Hostrup M, Hansen ESH, Rasmussen SM, Jessen S, Backer V. Asthma and exercise-induced bronchoconstriction in athletes: Diagnosis, treatment, and anti-doping challenges. Scand J Med Sci Sports. 2024; 34:e14358. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/sms.14358"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T15:12:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T15:12:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1740"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","posi